        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="112" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 <gloss target="#t_EAC1">EAC</gloss>/1–1945</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-19">January 19,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the President</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Agreement with regard to control Machinery for
                    Germany</p>
                <p>There is attached hereto a copy of my memorandum of November 25, 1944<note n="1" xml:id="d112fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_124">p. 124</ref>.</note>
                    recommending that you approve the agreement reached in the European Advisory
                    Commission with regard to control machinery for Germany.<note n="2" xml:id="d112fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_124">pp. 124</ref>–<ref target="#pg_127">127</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The members of the Commission were formally notified of the approval of this
                    agreement by the British Government on December 5, 1944 and similar approval by
                    the Soviet Government is expected momentarily. It is, therefore, a matter of the
                    utmost urgency that Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WJG1">Winant</persName> be
                    advised forthwith whether this basic document has the approval of the United
                    States, if we are to avoid placing ourselves in an embarrassing position in the
                    European Advisory Commission. It is for this reason that I urge you to give me
                    your decision on this agreement at your earliest convenience.</p>
                <p>The Secretary of War and the Secretary of Navy in a letter dated December 27,
                        1944,<note n="3" xml:id="d112fn3">Not printed.</note> which was received by
                    the Department of State on January 5, 1945, have recommended its approval.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SERJ1">E. R. <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius, Jr.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
